<PageLayout
  title="How to Format OpenAI Prompt Logs for Debugging"
  description="A practical guide to formatting OpenAI prompt logs: separate roles, unescape content, inspect tool calls, pretty-print JSON and keep sensitive data local."
  h1="How to Format OpenAI Prompt Logs for Debugging"
  path="/guides/format-openai-prompt-logs"
  article
  published="2026-07-09"
  updated="2026-07-20"
>
  <p>
    OpenAI prompt logs are often hard to read because the useful conversation is buried inside escaped
    JSON. System instructions, user messages, assistant output and tool payloads may all appear as one
    long line. Formatting the log turns it back into something you can inspect without losing the
    original meaning.
  </p>

  <p>
    Start with the <a href="/prompt">AI Prompt Formatter</a>. It is the first tool to use when a log
    contains LLM roles, escaped newlines or nested JSON, and it runs entirely in your browser.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the raw log before editing</h2>
  <p>
    Save the original log entry somewhere temporary before cleaning it. Formatting is for reading and
    debugging; the raw value is still the reference if you need to compare exact escaping, request
    fields or a reproduction case.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate system, user and assistant messages</h2>
  <p>
    The first debugging question is usually which role caused the behavior. Put each role in its own
    block so you can see whether the system message set the wrong constraints, the user message carried
    unexpected context or the assistant output introduced an invalid structure.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>System</strong>: policy, tone, task boundaries and hidden assumptions.</li>
    <li><strong>User</strong>: the actual request, pasted context and user-provided data.</li>
    <li><strong>Assistant</strong>: model output, intermediate drafts or response examples.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool</strong>: function arguments, tool results or structured payloads.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Unescape newlines before reading the prompt</h2>
  <p>
    Logs commonly show <code>\n</code>, <code>\t</code> and escaped quotes instead of readable text.
    Once those sequences are converted back into line breaks and indentation, prompt sections, Markdown
    lists and JSON examples become much easier to inspect. If the log is mostly an escaped string, try
    the <a href="/unescape-prompt">Unescape Prompt</a> page.
  </p>

  <h2>Pretty-print nested JSON separately</h2>
  <p>
    Prompt logs often include JSON fields such as message arrays, response formats, tool arguments or
    schema examples. When a nested block is hard to read, copy that specific JSON into
    <a href="/pretty-print-prompt-json">Pretty Print Prompt JSON</a> or the
    <a href="/json">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a>. This helps you spot missing quotes, invalid
    trailing commas and schema fields that are not where you expected.
  </p>

  <h2>Look for the smallest useful clue</h2>
  <p>
    Formatting a prompt log is not just cosmetic. It helps you narrow a failure down to a single
    instruction, value or message turn. After the log is readable, search for the smallest mismatch
    between what you expected and what the model actually received.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A system instruction that conflicts with the user request.</li>
    <li>A pasted document that lost headings or list structure.</li>
    <li>A JSON example that is invalid before the model ever sees it.</li>
    <li>A tool argument that was serialized as a string when the tool expected an object.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Be careful with sensitive data</h2>
  <p>
    Prompt logs can include customer text, API inputs, internal policies or personally identifiable
    information. Prefer browser-only tools for first-pass formatting, remove secrets before sharing a
    log with teammates and avoid posting raw production prompts in public issue trackers.
  </p>

  <h2>A practical workflow</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Open the <a href="/prompt">AI Prompt Formatter</a> and paste the copied log entry.</li>
    <li>Read the role blocks in order: system, user, assistant and tool messages.</li>
    <li>Use <a href="/json">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a> for any nested JSON that still looks broken.</li>
    <li>Use <a href="/markdown">Markdown Formatter &amp; Live Preview</a> if the prompt contains Markdown docs.</li>
    <li>Keep a cleaned version for debugging notes, but compare final fixes against the raw log.</li>
  </ul>

